While the increasing infection rate has been blamed on various factors, public transport has played a significant role.
Transport operators are well placed to prevent the spread of the infection. Urban public vehicles and long-distance travel, including trucks, should remain active participants in enforcing set Covid-19 prevention protocols.
Public transport parks are always overcrowded, especially by matatus. Peak hours present even more danger of infection as vehicles move slowly due to traffic congestion. Already in Nairobi, streets are heavily congested again.





A 2019 study on city traffic revealed that 42 per cent of Nairobians walk to work, 48 per cent use matatus, 5 per cent commute by private cars, while the remaining 5 per cent use other modes.
The research further estimated that during morning peak hours, the average vehicular speed is about 8.3 km/hour and 7.6 km/hour during the evening rush hour.
This shows that commuters in congested matatus and buses may be easily exposed to the risk of infection.
Public service operators 
At the onset of the pandemic, the Ministry of Transport adopted a raft of measures and issued directives aimed at reducing the spread of Covid-19 through public service vehicles. It directed that all buses and matatus and equipment therein be cleaned, disinfected and sanitised after every trip. 



